    <node id="Skin Rash">
      <data key="d0">Skin Rash</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Skin Rash is a dermatological symptom that presents as a skin manifestation associated with various clinical presentations. The condition manifests as a visible skin symptom that has been documented across multiple patient cases with differing underlying systemic conditions.

Skin Rash appears as an associated symptom alongside several musculoskeletal presentations, including knee conditions characterized by reduced range of motion and knee instability, hip instability, and shoulder instability. In these cases, the rash presents as part of a broader clinical picture that includes joint dysfunction and compromised mobility. The rash has been noted as a manifestation of systemic conditions that feature joint instability as a primary characteristic.

The temporal course of Skin Rash varies among presentations. In documented cases, the symptom has persisted for extended periods, with documented durations ranging from 5 months to 7 months or longer, indicating a chronic presentation pattern rather than an acute, self-limiting condition.

Skin Rash is recognized as an important clinical indicator during patient assessment, being noted during initial clinical presentation and physical examination. Its presence alongside musculoskeletal symptoms suggests a potential systemic or multisystem involvement rather than an isolated dermatological concern. The consistent association of skin rash with various joint instabilities and reduced mobility indicates it may serve as a clinical marker for underlying systemic pathology affecting both dermatological and musculoskeletal systems.&lt;SEP&gt;A dermatological symptom associated with the patient's musculoskeletal condition.&lt;SEP&gt;A skin rash is a cutaneous manifestation associated with the patient's condition.&lt;SEP&gt;A skin manifestation associated with the patient's underlying systemic condition.&lt;SEP&gt;A skin rash is a symptom associated with the patient's clinical presentation.&lt;SEP&gt;A cutaneous manifestation associated with the patient's musculoskeletal condition.&lt;SEP&gt;A dermatological symptom associated with the patient's musculoskeletal presentation.</data>
