    <node id="Osteoarthritis">
      <data key="d0">Osteoarthritis</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Osteoarthritis is a diagnosed musculoskeletal condition characterized by degenerative joint disease and progressive joint degeneration. The condition affects multiple joints throughout the patient's body, including the knee, shoulder, wrist, metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints, and sacroiliac joints. The degenerative changes associated with osteoarthritis have been confirmed through both imaging studies and laboratory findings, providing objective clinical evidence of the disease process.

The pathophysiology of osteoarthritis involves structural breakdown and degeneration of affected joint tissues. The condition manifests across various anatomical sites in the patient, with particular involvement of weight-bearing and frequently-used joints. The clinical presentation is consistent with degenerative joint disease patterns, where cartilage and underlying bone structure progressively deteriorate. The diagnosis has been established through comprehensive clinical evaluation, which incorporates radiological imaging findings and supporting laboratory results that collectively confirm the degenerative nature of the condition affecting the patient's musculoskeletal system.&lt;SEP&gt;The primary diagnosis given to the patient based on clinical presentation and diagnostic findings.&lt;SEP&gt;The diagnosis assigned to the patient based on clinical presentation, imaging findings, and laboratory results.&lt;SEP&gt;The diagnosed condition of the patient affecting the musculoskeletal system.</data>
