    <node id="EEG">
      <data key="d0">EEG</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Electroencephalography (EEG) is an electrophysiological diagnostic test used to record and assess electrical brain activity. The procedure involves recording electrical signals generated by the brain and serves as a diagnostic tool to evaluate neurological conditions and abnormalities in brain function. Healthcare professionals use EEG to objectively assess brain electrical activity and identify potential neurological abnormalities that may guide clinical decision-making and treatment planning. The test's ability to provide objective, measurable data about brain function makes it essential for comprehensive neurological assessment and management.

EEG examinations can yield varying results depending on an individual's neurological status. Some patients present with normal electroencephalogram recordings, indicating typical brain electrical activity with no significant abnormalities detected. Other patients exhibit abnormal patterns that require clinical attention and further investigation.

Common abnormal findings identified through EEG include several distinctive patterns. Focal slowing represents localized areas of reduced electrical activity within specific brain regions, indicating dysfunction in particular anatomical areas of the brain. This pattern has been observed in various patient assessments during EEG procedures. Generalized spike-and-wave discharges are characteristic electrical patterns that appear diffusely across the brain rather than being localized to a specific region, often associated with certain neurological conditions, particularly seizure disorders and epilepsy. Additionally, EEG can reveal burst suppression patterns, which indicate severe neurological abnormalities characterized by periods of electrical activity alternating with periods of relative electrical inactivity. This pattern has also been documented in patient EEG recordings.

EEG functions as an important diagnostic and monitoring tool in clinical practice, enabling healthcare professionals to detect and characterize various abnormal brain electrical patterns. By identifying these patterns—whether focal slowing, generalized spike-and-wave discharges, burst suppression, or normal activity—EEG facilitates appropriate diagnosis and treatment interventions for patients with neurological disorders.&lt;SEP&gt;Electroencephalography performed on the patient showing burst suppression pattern.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-571ddc4aa63fdf4b9d03942b5048b279&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b06c6a57e949da38959e52335f1e7ad5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ce7467c36645566972e9f92c5fea2ee8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-163a075cd3f1260ecb6825df91ee03e0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c3052227d42277d8826362c90a01ca5a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1911d102d00d5197ec74e282f36fbad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a34ac93aa94bca40ac3bced0aa9de86&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d4fd7d8854cca43bc54c0fae9bacd07a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d21fe1428431fa9900c5bdf9740d3490&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4881dc7c4d5f1079552b2430a7677765&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e95a6830eba771de7657ec415c1a31b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7e52b6e535af5d46b5f2606e7f3ba818&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-903baf97d86d9b7dd49873c2407977ae&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ba602c293552d3d1cc227f2fb935fe2c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6d9ce3f21c7d4f0447f68d282ddba6e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-035214426d6755454aa9eb73b6e0d4e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bbc516b53c71727bd08346a19ee50251&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6bd187f61bb50ddf67fed66dbf47414b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df174d639a33c9effb2f0ce6df80ce71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c15b0cde6ec5d9e10908aa2ac3619ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a0808ea5951fe6ba96ffa3ee735cda17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-84e342b229c6a006856ecdc1a267768a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f26c6d54ddb9d4b1f92d2f09061da7f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-66d79432cfb5da18b1aac0a6d772e676&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e3cde4a56707d1854488f0b25ff33596&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d94401800c111b74bf53e07ee0975662&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b934702b442931687944c3b680751df6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2747605a19dd90cae3b9e6a20d1194f3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1405b111c59c1691a48901cde2eed51b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f3b72ae1dccac058d727442c28727b3d</data>
