    <node id="Oesophageal Varices Grade III">
      <data key="d0">Oesophageal Varices Grade III</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Oesophageal Varices Grade III refers to severely enlarged veins in the oesophagus that are identified and classified during endoscopic examination. This condition represents an advanced stage of esophageal venous dilation and is indicative of severe portal hypertension. Grade III oesophageal varices are characterized by their substantial enlargement and are distinguished from lower grades by the degree of vein dilation observed during endoscopy. The endoscopic visualization of Grade III oesophageal varices is a critical diagnostic finding that reflects the progression of underlying portal hypertension, a condition commonly associated with chronic liver disease and cirrhosis. The classification of varices into Grade III severity serves as an important prognostic indicator for clinicians assessing the risk of variceal bleeding and determining appropriate management and treatment strategies for affected patients.&lt;SEP&gt;Dilated veins in the oesophagus of grade III severity demonstrated on endoscopy, a complication of liver disease.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-913dac86f1445586ee7313cee3abcef4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-299e0d28d253c37f9dddf4aef8eb2c94&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6540caa7beb945f0321bf38942587d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32a4845ff65651415af840aed5ad1767&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-caa60f44fc47125398c7ec53a5186865&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93cc887c0186b2515e2821eabf31639d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-735be7666813a3f1eedf039a72df5db3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b832bffca6f5b953e97047ac37cd38ec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f78e14c615a6efcb86bacdcef718021</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168993</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="CT Abdomen">
      <data key="d0">CT Abdomen</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">CT Abdomen is a computed tomography imaging procedure of the abdominal region that serves as a comprehensive diagnostic tool for visualizing abdominal structures and organs with high resolution. This advanced radiological imaging modality is employed in clinical practice to detect, identify, and characterize various pathological conditions affecting the abdomen, playing a crucial role in diagnosis, staging, and monitoring of abdominal disease.

CT Abdomen is utilized to identify multiple clinically significant findings. One primary pathological finding detected through this imaging procedure is intrahepatic biliary dilatation, which represents dilation of the bile ducts within the liver parenchyma. This finding indicates compromised biliary drainage or obstruction within the hepatic system. The imaging procedure is also used to detect hepatic metastases, enabling identification and characterization of secondary malignant lesions within the liver tissue. This capability makes CT Abdomen valuable for oncological assessment and staging purposes, allowing clinicians to evaluate the extent of malignant disease.

CT Abdomen is employed to identify circumferential colonic thickening, which involves assessment of the colonic wall and detection of abnormal thickening that extends around the circumference of the colon. This finding is significant in evaluating colonic pathology, including inflammatory bowel disease, malignancy, or other structural abnormalities. Furthermore, CT Abdomen can reveal portal hypertension, a condition characterized by elevated pressure within the portal venous system, and splenomegaly, which refers to enlargement of the spleen. These hepatic findings are often interconnected and may indicate chronic liver disease or other systemic conditions affecting hepatic hemodynamics.

Overall, CT Abdomen serves as an essential diagnostic imaging method capable of detecting multiple abdominal pathologies and providing valuable clinical information for patient management and treatment planning.&lt;SEP&gt;A computed tomography imaging procedure of the abdominal region.&lt;SEP&gt;A computed tomography imaging study of the abdominal region revealing intrahepatic biliary dilatation.&lt;SEP&gt;Imaging study of the abdomen used to identify hepatic metastases.&lt;SEP&gt;Imaging technique used to detect portal hypertension and splenomegaly.&lt;SEP&gt;A computed tomography imaging procedure of the abdomen that revealed portal hypertension and splenomegaly.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-913dac86f1445586ee7313cee3abcef4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed0783f447cb66336d0ee665a9a9ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17baf644d96495d064f9649f631230b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0cf79a93d6937f4e196efd0a76b1c14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed28d4753317331d50864a0ff241202a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-552541f5707dbc91dc2b39f24da42ff3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-359c4bdb901dcb37d2cf0fa307a2c571&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b0848622c01d4f566da1895987417746&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-299e0d28d253c37f9dddf4aef8eb2c94&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5efbbabff30dce7757a05e1d7b57eaa2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93f288f93598c3b3a931faed20b2314c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4fb8802354fa5826fc6a61e1d4703650&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6540caa7beb945f0321bf38942587d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-42c5dd7e4b8ae3efca148f8d10f468da&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7dfbf9ae7bdd2da18160509a98a29b9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32a4845ff65651415af840aed5ad1767&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aea77867f87b397c2569ebf2e109e550&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d50fc57a8c14c7819b2950816abc682&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-caa60f44fc47125398c7ec53a5186865&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2af3da83b586005637f4530b60892346&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-12b0793fd5ff30936be7578fadb2f11c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-389cb396bf4e6268fa31af66e862032b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93cc887c0186b2515e2821eabf31639d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-735be7666813a3f1eedf039a72df5db3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17ee3298badd5c634297742f3bfdd8e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd08cbda0f2618e783e7d18b1e718420&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9bd68a770018591cf0e4611e9e14ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b832bffca6f5b953e97047ac37cd38ec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1693a9d96722a090fabd3e1bd2ba20a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dbdb6e100fb2bdb409feb08c479fa265&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d99b348010e0859bf79ca469b926378b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f78e14c615a6efcb86bacdcef718021&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-304f340ad4cf36f85eadeea2200b5890&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1375b9b5b2e11625f9232d34b4107e38</data>
