    <node id="Intrahepatic Biliary Dilatation">
      <data key="d0">Intrahepatic Biliary Dilatation</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Intrahepatic biliary dilatation is a radiological finding characterized by abnormal widening or enlargement of the bile ducts within the liver. This condition is typically identified and demonstrated on CT abdomen imaging, where it appears as a structural abnormality visible on cross-sectional imaging. The condition represents a pathological change in the hepatic biliary system that can be detected through computed tomography examination, serving as an important diagnostic indicator of potential underlying hepatobiliary pathology.&lt;SEP&gt;A radiological finding on CT abdomen indicating dilated bile ducts within the liver tissue.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-913dac86f1445586ee7313cee3abcef4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed28d4753317331d50864a0ff241202a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-552541f5707dbc91dc2b39f24da42ff3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93f288f93598c3b3a931faed20b2314c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6540caa7beb945f0321bf38942587d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-42c5dd7e4b8ae3efca148f8d10f468da&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-389cb396bf4e6268fa31af66e862032b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9bd68a770018591cf0e4611e9e14ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d99b348010e0859bf79ca469b926378b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168989</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Liver Biopsy">
      <data key="d0">Liver Biopsy</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Liver Biopsy is a tissue sampling diagnostic procedure employed to obtain and analyze liver tissue samples for the confirmation of various hepatic and systemic conditions. The procedure involves extracting liver tissue, which then undergoes pathological examination to identify and confirm the presence of disease through histopathological evidence.

Liver biopsy serves as a definitive diagnostic tool for confirming primary liver malignancies. It is utilized to diagnose hepatocellular carcinoma, the primary malignancy of the liver, by directly sampling tissue to identify cancerous cells and establish a definitive diagnosis. The procedure has also been employed to confirm adenocarcinoma within liver tissue, allowing pathologists to identify malignant cellular changes and provide conclusive diagnostic evidence.

Beyond malignant neoplasms, liver biopsy plays a significant role in assessing fibrotic and cirrhotic conditions. The procedure enables confirmation of cirrhosis with bridging fibrosis, providing comprehensive assessment of the extent and severity of liver damage, including the degree of fibrotic changes and architectural distortion of the hepatic parenchyma. This application allows clinicians to evaluate the progressive nature of chronic liver disease and stage the degree of hepatic compromise.

Additionally, liver biopsy functions as a diagnostic instrument for confirming systemic diseases with hepatic manifestations. Notably, the procedure has been utilized to confirm Crohn's disease, an inflammatory bowel condition that can present with extraintestinal manifestations affecting various organs, including the liver. This demonstrates that liver biopsy serves not only as a tool for identifying primary liver diseases but also as a diagnostic instrument for detecting secondary hepatic involvement in systemic inflammatory disorders.

Overall, liver biopsy represents a definitive diagnostic approach that provides the histopathological evidence necessary for confirming a diverse range of conditions affecting the liver, from primary malignancies and fibrotic diseases to secondary manifestations of systemic inflammatory conditions.&lt;SEP&gt;A tissue sampling procedure of the liver to confirm diagnosis.&lt;SEP&gt;A tissue sampling procedure that confirmed the diagnosis of hepatocellular carcinoma.&lt;SEP&gt;Tissue sampling procedure that confirmed cirrhosis with bridging fibrosis.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagnostic procedure used to confirm hepatocellular carcinoma.&lt;SEP&gt;A tissue sampling procedure of the liver that confirmed Crohn's disease.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-913dac86f1445586ee7313cee3abcef4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed0783f447cb66336d0ee665a9a9ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17baf644d96495d064f9649f631230b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e0cf79a93d6937f4e196efd0a76b1c14&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ed28d4753317331d50864a0ff241202a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-552541f5707dbc91dc2b39f24da42ff3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-359c4bdb901dcb37d2cf0fa307a2c571&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b0848622c01d4f566da1895987417746&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-299e0d28d253c37f9dddf4aef8eb2c94&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5efbbabff30dce7757a05e1d7b57eaa2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93f288f93598c3b3a931faed20b2314c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4fb8802354fa5826fc6a61e1d4703650&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6540caa7beb945f0321bf38942587d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-42c5dd7e4b8ae3efca148f8d10f468da&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7dfbf9ae7bdd2da18160509a98a29b9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32a4845ff65651415af840aed5ad1767&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aea77867f87b397c2569ebf2e109e550&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d50fc57a8c14c7819b2950816abc682&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-caa60f44fc47125398c7ec53a5186865&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2af3da83b586005637f4530b60892346&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-12b0793fd5ff30936be7578fadb2f11c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-389cb396bf4e6268fa31af66e862032b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93cc887c0186b2515e2821eabf31639d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-735be7666813a3f1eedf039a72df5db3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17ee3298badd5c634297742f3bfdd8e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd08cbda0f2618e783e7d18b1e718420&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9bd68a770018591cf0e4611e9e14ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b832bffca6f5b953e97047ac37cd38ec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1693a9d96722a090fabd3e1bd2ba20a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dbdb6e100fb2bdb409feb08c479fa265&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d99b348010e0859bf79ca469b926378b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f78e14c615a6efcb86bacdcef718021&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-304f340ad4cf36f85eadeea2200b5890&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1375b9b5b2e11625f9232d34b4107e38</data>
