    <node id="Skin Biopsy">
      <data key="d0">Skin Biopsy</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Skin Biopsy is a diagnostic and histopathological procedure that involves the extraction and microscopic examination of tissue samples obtained from skin lesions. This procedure serves as a critical tool in dermatopathology, enabling clinicians to identify, characterize, and differentiate various dermatological conditions through detailed tissue analysis.

The procedure functions by obtaining tissue samples directly from the affected skin lesion, which are then subjected to histopathological examination under microscopic analysis. This examination allows for definitive identification of lesion characteristics and determination of malignancy status, thereby guiding appropriate clinical management and patient care decisions.

Skin biopsy has been utilized to diagnose multiple conditions across different cases. In malignant cases, the procedure has identified malignant melanoma, with Breslow thickness measurements recorded to assess tumor depth and invasion—a metric particularly significant for melanoma staging, prognosis assessment, and treatment planning. Notably, one documented case identified malignant melanoma with a Breslow thickness of 1.2 mm. Additionally, skin biopsy has confirmed the presence of nodular basal cell carcinoma and squamous cell carcinoma in situ, both forms of skin cancer that are definitively diagnosed through tissue analysis.

Beyond malignant neoplasms, skin biopsy has also revealed inflammatory and non-malignant conditions. The procedure has identified psoriasis, characterized by specific histological features including acanthosis and parakeratosis—terms describing the thickening of the epidermis and retention of keratin within the stratum corneum, respectively. Through tissue examination, clinicians can effectively distinguish between malignant neoplasms such as melanoma, basal cell carcinoma, and squamous cell carcinoma in situ, as well as benign or inflammatory dermatological conditions, thereby enabling accurate diagnosis and appropriate therapeutic intervention.&lt;SEP&gt;A pathological examination that identified nodular basal cell carcinoma in the lesion tissue.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagnostic procedure that confirmed the presence of nodular basal cell carcinoma.&lt;SEP&gt;A diagnostic procedure performed to extract and analyze skin tissue, which revealed squamous cell carcinoma in situ.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8176cddaae4d68a2202fd24c008d9124&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f55f588d05d3c94a3e19fa2baa547f4d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1833ee3771fdd057cb4b4d8971b96a1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6832ceabd069924c459708223a28ba62&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-753f2b2c76f5884bcc21bf4f615442cc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4b2d5f8876ed45c5eb097f53215c03ef&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6fefabc1e665ca1162ec747e9ecad131&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9712a596a557320744b8555237d23730&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-81df5ef7a4ba33b8c9c8661a3dfabcaa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4c60f4b4404d3d935bf9d0334c2044fa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a185cf1750f40bf2fcc7a6769dd25c5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dfaaca9bc6d86852ae2e8758043f9795&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-88719264befc27293ac742a7e9abf0c2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b5549f54f3a70ba226eb2c6771d9bfa2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bf57c7666f58268cb9b55a024ab50566&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-36fd271447be9f1bd7be85292d8a1b54&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-41110817cee95604f38a1c263881cb91&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8cf6c15302e70e0980453665ab84f278</data>
