    <node id="Joint Space Narrowing">
      <data key="d0">Joint Space Narrowing</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Joint Space Narrowing is a radiological finding observed on X-ray imaging that indicates the reduction of space between joint surfaces due to cartilage loss and degenerative changes. This finding reflects progressive degradation of the affected joint and is a key radiographic indicator of joint degeneration.

Joint space narrowing can be identified across multiple anatomical locations throughout the body. In the knee joint, it appears as a radiographic finding on X-ray indicating cartilage loss within the knee joint space. In the hip, joint space narrowing is observed on X-ray as a radiological sign of degenerative changes affecting the hip joint. In the shoulder joint, it manifests as a radiological finding indicating both degradation of the shoulder joint space and reduced space between joint surfaces, serving as a sign of joint degeneration. Joint space narrowing is also documented in the spine, where it appears as a radiological finding indicating reduced spacing between vertebral joint surfaces. Additionally, this finding can be observed in the wrist and metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints, where it indicates degenerative joint changes.

The presence of joint space narrowing on radiographic examination represents an important clinical sign of osteoarthritic changes and progressive joint deterioration. Across all affected anatomical sites—whether in the knee, hip, shoulder, spine, wrist, or MCPs—the fundamental pathology involves cartilage loss and the resultant reduction in the distance between articulating bone surfaces, which can be visualized and assessed through X-ray imaging.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-010177962773e82b3b10b0765421d512&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c89e4f390f742775decbbc049992e1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a10d7b819d49867b6e7814e98a516ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68e7577c18cbc865ebf744daec101377&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3303df334fce5c6456df7e61e6203291&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d5688d8714c141858552becb5c4be710&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-931d7f0d4f1634c02440df1aacdef13c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e2125b75a0cbbb2f0ed02f43f4bdbc9f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168678</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Osteophytes">
      <data key="d0">Osteophytes</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Osteophytes are bone spurs that develop as a result of degenerative joint disease. These abnormal bony growths can be identified and visualized through X-ray imaging across multiple locations in the body.

Osteophytes have been documented in various joints throughout the skeletal system. In the knee joint, bone spurs are commonly revealed on X-ray imaging and may be identified in patients presenting with degenerative changes. In the hip, osteophytes are characteristic findings on X-ray that indicate the presence of degenerative joint disease. The shoulder joint frequently exhibits osteophytes, which are detected through shoulder X-ray imaging as bone spur formations. In the spine, bone spurs can be identified on X-ray imaging as part of degenerative processes affecting the vertebral column. Additionally, osteophytes occur in the wrist and metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints, where they are revealed on X-ray as manifestations of degenerative joint disease.

Osteophytes represent a common radiological finding associated with joint degeneration, and their presence across multiple joint sites suggests a systemic degenerative process. X-ray imaging remains the primary diagnostic tool for identifying and documenting the presence and extent of bone spurs in affected joints.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-010177962773e82b3b10b0765421d512&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c89e4f390f742775decbbc049992e1b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a10d7b819d49867b6e7814e98a516ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-68e7577c18cbc865ebf744daec101377&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3303df334fce5c6456df7e61e6203291&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d5688d8714c141858552becb5c4be710&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-931d7f0d4f1634c02440df1aacdef13c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e2125b75a0cbbb2f0ed02f43f4bdbc9f</data>
