    <node id="Ankle Swelling">
      <data key="d0">Ankle Swelling</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Ankle swelling is a clinical symptom characterized by fluid accumulation and swelling in the ankle region. It represents a form of peripheral edema, which is the abnormal accumulation of fluid in tissues, particularly in the extremities. This symptom has been consistently reported by patients during clinical assessments and medical admissions.

Ankle swelling manifests as a physical manifestation of localized edema in the ankle area. The condition is identified through patient reporting during clinical evaluation and physical examination. As a component of peripheral edema, ankle swelling indicates underlying fluid retention or circulatory issues affecting the lower extremities. The symptom serves as an important clinical indicator that may warrant further investigation to determine its underlying etiology, which could range from cardiovascular, renal, hepatic, or lymphatic causes to local inflammatory or mechanical factors.&lt;SEP&gt;Ankle swelling reported by the patient as an additional symptom.&lt;SEP&gt;Ankle swelling is a symptom reported by the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Ankle swelling is an additional symptom reported by the patient during admission.&lt;SEP&gt;A symptom reported by the patient, indicating potential systemic involvement.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-556d7ea1921560596bb0c596a00bdf0a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-937e867ddae2f8daaa79bd2e639976eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-92cc2c46c1f49338ed7955ea4238e60f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e7f38ad205281fc2b3d3fdc52c5a8b5c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d69e90de14f13f99bd017794598000f5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b29acdc1599ff32318f1144aaa062a2b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-50c06f071bd4436025fb35de50515fda&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b74bdb93da896529bce41ee41924095c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8e4a466aae7fe4bee947643e66e2ba9c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a71fb455018aca9558b624f3b05ab137&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c51e9f120ecce8be89d00fb7954cbe1a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d4f335b1b7bae18006bc038ab4128db1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775169168</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Smoking History">
      <data key="d0">Smoking History</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Smoking History

A patient's smoking history is documented at 40 pack-years, representing a substantial cumulative smoking exposure. This metric is calculated by multiplying the number of packs smoked per day by the number of years of smoking, and the 40 pack-year figure indicates significant long-term tobacco use. This smoking history constitutes a relevant and important medical risk factor that must be considered in clinical assessment and patient management.

The 40 pack-year smoking history is particularly significant as it represents a well-established risk factor for respiratory disease. This level of smoking exposure increases the patient's susceptibility to various pulmonary conditions and complications. The documented smoking exposure is clinically relevant to understanding the patient's current medical presentation and predisposition to smoking-related health conditions. This historical information is essential for comprehensive patient evaluation, risk stratification, and appropriate clinical decision-making regarding prevention, screening, and treatment strategies related to smoking-associated morbidity.&lt;SEP&gt;The patient's history of smoking totaling 40 pack-years, a relevant clinical factor.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-556d7ea1921560596bb0c596a00bdf0a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-937e867ddae2f8daaa79bd2e639976eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d29c25e21e325edd849f3dc97bf8a04&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f5543cdd6c57fb9e70e4d6b2688e3521&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3758214300d6bd794534d0e32e9bd057&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3fa76722cb250ebdc3971241f8d1d7a1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aeb696350165bf9ae41216f5236c3817&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8ab7539afd48876f5bb300e184ed79b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d4f335b1b7bae18006bc038ab4128db1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775169168</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Chest X-Ray">
      <data key="d0">Chest X-Ray</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Chest X-Ray is a diagnostic imaging procedure used to examine the patient's thoracic cavity, lungs, and respiratory system through radiographic techniques. This imaging modality visualizes the internal structures of the chest and serves as a critical tool for detecting various pathological conditions affecting the lungs and surrounding tissues.

In clinical practice, chest X-rays have documented multiple significant pathological findings across various patients. Common radiographic abnormalities include bilateral infiltrates, indicating the presence of fluid or inflammatory material distributed across both lungs, and right upper lobe consolidation, suggesting areas of lung tissue that have become solid or filled with fluid or pus in the right upper portion of the lungs. Right lower lobe consolidation has also been identified in certain imaging studies. Pleural effusion, characterized by the abnormal accumulation of fluid between the layers of the pleura surrounding the lungs, has been consistently documented across multiple examinations. Additionally, some chest X-rays have revealed left-sided pneumothorax, indicating collapsed lung tissue on the left side.

Bilateral hyperinflation of the lungs has been noted in some patients, characterized by overdistension of the lungs with increased air content, reflecting potential obstructive airway disease or air-trapping mechanisms. Air trapping on expiratory films has suggested bronchial foreign body obstruction in at least one case. Collectively, these radiographic findings indicate complex pulmonary processes affecting patients, with evidence of inflammatory and infectious changes such as infiltrates and consolidation, abnormal fluid accumulation in the pleural space, potential mechanical obstruction and air-trapping mechanisms, and in some cases, lung collapse or foreign body obstruction.

Chest X-ray remains an essential diagnostic tool in identifying and documenting thoracic abnormalities, which typically warrant further clinical correlation and possibly additional diagnostic imaging or laboratory studies to determine the underlying etiology and guide appropriate clinical management.&lt;SEP&gt;Imaging examination that revealed left-sided pneumothorax in the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Imaging study showing air trapping on expiratory film consistent with bronchial foreign body.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-556d7ea1921560596bb0c596a00bdf0a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-937e867ddae2f8daaa79bd2e639976eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7cfa77dcd4a2e473aabe4108bc1732c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d29c25e21e325edd849f3dc97bf8a04&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-348a6f93e1df4665db6794f8f475315a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3758214300d6bd794534d0e32e9bd057&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-92cc2c46c1f49338ed7955ea4238e60f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf05a1180370ca5c22ffbfcdb89ab2d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e7f38ad205281fc2b3d3fdc52c5a8b5c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c41f1161752e203627b5fc920fca07&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-633b98afe9675d274497d13c770dc7a8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d69e90de14f13f99bd017794598000f5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-50c06f071bd4436025fb35de50515fda&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-edefebc0c0ccf297dd9120097036b554&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd85436604dc21edf42918a59c026df6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c464148080eca020535a45a857530061&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e94bd709d2e35b86324f9ebf8cb380f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b74bdb93da896529bce41ee41924095c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-11ac0d1d3c9697cf3ad1c05e8e52ee8a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3fa76722cb250ebdc3971241f8d1d7a1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ea49e51c9a44c10ef5253c942a3bd509&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-125eccf021b8ac36d38facc6f2707698&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8ef20424effc0d32c39fcdcec5da83d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dda6359792d27d913bf9dbba5833f91f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c4cc1d83b1ff0beb41c0996e0bed59f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ebdec2fe609dbeb73244f6c370f4d8eb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aeb696350165bf9ae41216f5236c3817&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8ab7539afd48876f5bb300e184ed79b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a71fb455018aca9558b624f3b05ab137&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb2cd72190b2ba60ab4d0ac08898df5c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e5211c9d4452573a55519727c0ef76b1</data>
