    <node id="Fever">
      <data key="d0">Fever</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Fever is a clinical symptom characterized by an elevated body temperature that has been reported in the patient's presentation. The symptom manifests as an increase in body temperature, with documented instances reaching 38.9°C. Fever appears as a component of the patient's overall clinical presentation and symptomatology.

The patient's fever presentation varies in duration and context. In some instances, fever has been documented with a 2-day history prior to arrival at the clinical facility. In other cases, the patient experienced a prolonged fever lasting 28 days as noted in the clinical history. Fever has also been reported as a symptom accompanying other clinical manifestations, specifically in conjunction with haemoptysis and stridor.

Throughout the patient's clinical course, fever has been consistently identified as an elevated body temperature symptom reported as part of the documented clinical presentation and patient-reported symptoms.&lt;SEP&gt;A symptom presenting in the patient with a 1-day history prior to hospital admission.&lt;SEP&gt;A symptom reported by the patient during admission.&lt;SEP&gt;A 10-day history of elevated body temperature experienced by the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Fever is an elevated body temperature symptom reported by the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Elevated body temperature reported by the patient as a symptom accompanying chest pain and wheeze.&lt;SEP&gt;A symptom experienced by the patient for 21 days prior to presentation.</data>
