    <node id="Endobronchial Tumour">
      <data key="d0">Endobronchial Tumour</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">An endobronchial tumour is an abnormal growth or neoplasm located within the bronchial airways of the respiratory system. This pathological condition represents a tumour situated in the bronchial tree, which comprises the branching passages that conduct air from the trachea to the lungs. Endobronchial tumours are typically identified and detected during bronchoscopy, a diagnostic procedure in which a flexible or rigid instrument is inserted into the airways to directly visualize and examine the internal structures of the bronchial passages. The bronchoscopic examination allows clinicians to observe the presence of these abnormal growths within the bronchial airways and obtain samples for further pathological analysis if necessary. Endobronchial tumours represent a significant clinical finding requiring appropriate investigation and management to determine their nature, extent, and potential impact on respiratory function.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-3d29c25e21e325edd849f3dc97bf8a04&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6c35da8135a5d590d4accdb1b51d149c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf05a1180370ca5c22ffbfcdb89ab2d9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-27c41f1161752e203627b5fc920fca07&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b74bdb93da896529bce41ee41924095c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8e4a466aae7fe4bee947643e66e2ba9c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aeb696350165bf9ae41216f5236c3817&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e8ab7539afd48876f5bb300e184ed79b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
