    <node id="Gout">
      <data key="d0">Gout</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Gout is a metabolic disorder characterized by inflammation of the joints caused by the deposition of monosodium urate crystals. The condition is diagnosed through the identification of negatively birefringent crystals in synovial fluid and is associated with elevated uric acid levels in the body. Clinically, gout presents with joint pain and swelling, representing an inflammatory joint disease directly related to hyperuricemia (elevated uric acid).

The diagnosis of gout requires appropriate clinical and laboratory correlation. In some cases, gout may be diagnosed in patients presenting with spinal instability and various clinical findings. However, notably, gout can sometimes be diagnosed despite clinical presentations and test results that appear inconsistent with the typical manifestations of the condition, highlighting the complexity of diagnostic decision-making in certain clinical scenarios.

Management of gout involves the use of specific medications tailored to address the underlying metabolic disorder and alleviate symptoms. The condition's diagnosis and subsequent treatment planning are essential components of patient care, requiring careful consideration of both clinical presentation and laboratory findings to ensure accurate identification and effective therapeutic intervention.&lt;SEP&gt;Gout is the diagnosed condition characterized by inflammatory joint disease with elevated WBC in synovial fluid and chondrocalcinosis on imaging.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dc908789d613380f6cd7ce177b5dfafb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d5ef4a9ff207d5fcf312fa4948419500&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6f3968a1e0f64443d559f9c75594cad0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0ff99b3fbcf99c238b4ecf7d0e0a7afc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-05e39d703a228f9f75806162f2ec5ed2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a667de4da28bb439da82a6fd3153ca1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4a10d7b819d49867b6e7814e98a516ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-86ab66027f34b355354509e6cc65735e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-606a0358ec61458bc198d5e4d438844f</data>
