    <node id="Haemarthrosis">
      <data key="d0">Haemarthrosis</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Haemarthrosis is the accumulation of blood in the joint space, a condition characterized by the presence of blood within the synovial fluid of affected joints. This pathological finding is typically identified and confirmed through synovial fluid analysis, a diagnostic procedure that examines the fluid present within the joint cavity. The condition can affect various joints throughout the body, including the knee joint, where blood accumulation in the joint space represents a significant clinical finding. The detection of blood in the synovial fluid serves as the primary diagnostic indicator of haemarthrosis, allowing healthcare professionals to confirm the presence of intra-articular bleeding and assess the severity of the condition in patients presenting with joint-related symptoms.&lt;SEP&gt;Blood in the synovial fluid, identified through synovial fluid analysis.&lt;SEP&gt;Haemarthrosis is the presence of blood in the joint space, detected through synovial fluid analysis.&lt;SEP&gt;Blood accumulation in the joint space detected in synovial fluid analysis.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dc908789d613380f6cd7ce177b5dfafb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c49c05a874ce6761c157c4e35dd9903b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0ff99b3fbcf99c238b4ecf7d0e0a7afc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1de22df34c77d7bc601fa40ded28a01&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3303df334fce5c6456df7e61e6203291&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b2c623dc26c99ebd3a6caf0a7b69babb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-57d53deb985a155d9d6cc2e16d224de8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7c81af782e89b002c04a944dc0cea584&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-86ab66027f34b355354509e6cc65735e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d5688d8714c141858552becb5c4be710&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22ab2cc7fede189ebd9f80f76a17ce09</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168539</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Soft Tissue Swelling">
      <data key="d0">Soft Tissue Swelling</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Soft Tissue Swelling is a radiological finding detected on X-ray imaging that represents inflammation or edema in soft tissues surrounding affected joints and anatomical regions throughout the body. This condition can be identified across multiple anatomical sites, including the wrist, metacarpophalangeal (MCP) joints, spine, shoulder, and knee.

When observed in the wrist and metacarpophalangeal joints, soft tissue swelling appears on X-ray imaging as inflammation in the soft tissues surrounding these affected joints. Similarly, in the spine, X-ray findings indicate swelling or edema in the soft tissues associated with spinal structures. In the shoulder region, soft tissue swelling is revealed through X-ray imaging as visible swelling of the soft tissues. The condition also manifests in the knee, where X-ray imaging can detect soft tissue swelling in this joint area.

Soft tissue swelling serves as an important radiological indicator of inflammatory or pathological processes affecting the joints and surrounding anatomical structures, making it a clinically relevant finding in diagnostic imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Inflammation of soft tissues in the knee observed on X-ray imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Swelling in soft tissues surrounding the hip joint detected on X-ray imaging.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-dc908789d613380f6cd7ce177b5dfafb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d5ef4a9ff207d5fcf312fa4948419500&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6f3968a1e0f64443d559f9c75594cad0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5da01a385b47958d437c2b60db9a3505&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-05e39d703a228f9f75806162f2ec5ed2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8a667de4da28bb439da82a6fd3153ca1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1367d2b19d4c80169f6e3f681823cd2c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-57d53deb985a155d9d6cc2e16d224de8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-996a573759ff4451282c4bad9069e599&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22ab2cc7fede189ebd9f80f76a17ce09</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168539</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="IV Alteplase Thrombolysis">
      <data key="d0">IV Alteplase Thrombolysis</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">IV Alteplase Thrombolysis is an intravenous thrombolytic treatment that involves the administration of alteplase, a thrombolytic agent, to patients as part of their treatment regimen or protocol. This therapeutic intervention is designed to dissolve blood clots and restore normal blood flow through the affected vessels.

IV Alteplase Thrombolysis is particularly utilized in the management of ischaemic stroke, where timely administration of the thrombolytic agent is critical to restore cerebral perfusion and minimize tissue damage. The alteplase works by activating the fibrinolytic cascade, breaking down fibrin-based clots that obstruct blood vessels and impede circulation. By restoring adequate blood flow, this treatment helps prevent further ischemic damage and improves patient outcomes in acute thrombotic conditions.&lt;SEP&gt;Intravenous alteplase thrombolytic therapy administered to the patient as treatment for ischaemic stroke.&lt;SEP&gt;A treatment modality involving intravenous administration of alteplase for thrombolytic purposes.&lt;SEP&gt;IV alteplase thrombolysis is a treatment method using intravenous alteplase to dissolve blood clots.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b06c6a57e949da38959e52335f1e7ad5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ce7467c36645566972e9f92c5fea2ee8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-163a075cd3f1260ecb6825df91ee03e0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1911d102d00d5197ec74e282f36fbad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4881dc7c4d5f1079552b2430a7677765&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6d9ce3f21c7d4f0447f68d282ddba6e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-035214426d6755454aa9eb73b6e0d4e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6bd187f61bb50ddf67fed66dbf47414b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c15b0cde6ec5d9e10908aa2ac3619ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2747605a19dd90cae3b9e6a20d1194f3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1405b111c59c1691a48901cde2eed51b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775169186</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Antiplatelet Therapy">
      <data key="d0">Antiplatelet Therapy</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Antiplatelet Therapy is a pharmacological treatment approach that uses medications designed to inhibit platelet aggregation and prevent blood clot formation. This therapeutic intervention works to improve circulation and reduce the risk of thrombotic events by preventing platelets from clumping together and forming clots that could obstruct blood vessels.

Antiplatelet Therapy is frequently administered as a secondary treatment following intravenous thrombolysis, particularly after IV alteplase administration. In this context, the therapy serves as a crucial follow-up intervention to prevent clot reformation and reduce the recurrence of ischemic events such as stroke. By maintaining platelet inhibition after the initial thrombolytic intervention has dissolved an existing clot, antiplatelet agents help sustain improved circulation and protect against secondary thrombotic complications.

The clinical application of Antiplatelet Therapy involves the administration of antiplatelet agents to patients as part of a comprehensive treatment strategy aimed at improving clinical outcomes and reducing morbidity associated with thromboembolic conditions. The medications function by interfering with platelet function and aggregation pathways, thereby lowering the overall risk of clot formation and related cardiovascular or cerebrovascular events.&lt;SEP&gt;Antiplatelet medication administered to the patient following thrombolysis to prevent recurrent stroke.&lt;SEP&gt;A therapeutic approach used following thrombolysis to prevent platelet aggregation and thrombotic events.&lt;SEP&gt;Antiplatelet therapy is a treatment method using medications to prevent platelet aggregation and blood clot formation.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b06c6a57e949da38959e52335f1e7ad5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ce7467c36645566972e9f92c5fea2ee8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-163a075cd3f1260ecb6825df91ee03e0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1911d102d00d5197ec74e282f36fbad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4881dc7c4d5f1079552b2430a7677765&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b6d9ce3f21c7d4f0447f68d282ddba6e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-035214426d6755454aa9eb73b6e0d4e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6bd187f61bb50ddf67fed66dbf47414b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2c15b0cde6ec5d9e10908aa2ac3619ac&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2747605a19dd90cae3b9e6a20d1194f3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1405b111c59c1691a48901cde2eed51b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775169186</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Motor Improvement">
      <data key="d0">Motor Improvement</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Motor Improvement is a positive clinical outcome characterized by significant improvement in motor function observed in patients at discharge following treatment. This outcome indicates that patients have achieved enhanced motor capabilities as a direct result of the administered therapeutic interventions. Motor improvement represents a measurable and clinically meaningful recovery in motor function, demonstrating the effectiveness of treatment protocols in restoring or enhancing patients' physical motor abilities at the point of hospital discharge or treatment completion.&lt;SEP&gt;Significant improvement in motor function observed in the patient at discharge.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-b06c6a57e949da38959e52335f1e7ad5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-163a075cd3f1260ecb6825df91ee03e0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1911d102d00d5197ec74e282f36fbad9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-035214426d6755454aa9eb73b6e0d4e1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6bd187f61bb50ddf67fed66dbf47414b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df174d639a33c9effb2f0ce6df80ce71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a0808ea5951fe6ba96ffa3ee735cda17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-84e342b229c6a006856ecdc1a267768a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-66d79432cfb5da18b1aac0a6d772e676&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e3cde4a56707d1854488f0b25ff33596</data>
