    <node id="Rectal Bleeding">
      <data key="d0">Rectal Bleeding</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Rectal bleeding is a gastrointestinal symptom characterized by bleeding from the rectum that presents as a primary complaint prompting clinical evaluation and investigation. Across documented cases, rectal bleeding has manifested with varying durations, ranging from as brief as one week to as prolonged as twenty-eight weeks. 

In clinical presentations, rectal bleeding has been recorded with durations of one week, two weeks, three weeks, five weeks, seven weeks, fourteen weeks, and twenty-eight weeks. When rectal bleeding persists for approximately three weeks, it may be associated with additional gastrointestinal symptoms including nausea, vomiting, and dark urine, which collectively indicate more significant underlying gastrointestinal pathology.

Rectal bleeding functions as a primary presenting symptom that typically motivates patients to seek medical attention and undergo diagnostic evaluation. The symptom's presence and duration are clinically significant, as they help guide the investigative process to identify the underlying gastrointestinal condition responsible for the bleeding. The variability in duration across different presentations suggests that rectal bleeding may arise from diverse gastrointestinal conditions, each with distinct clinical courses and severity profiles. Regardless of the specific duration or associated symptoms, rectal bleeding remains an important clinical indicator warranting thorough gastrointestinal assessment and diagnosis.&lt;SEP&gt;Rectal bleeding lasting 21 weeks duration, a primary symptom presenting in the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Rectal bleeding lasting 10 weeks duration that is associated with altered bowel habit and anorexia in the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Rectal bleeding lasting 7 weeks duration, a primary symptom presented by the patient.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ed0783f447cb66336d0ee665a9a9ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-299e0d28d253c37f9dddf4aef8eb2c94&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93f288f93598c3b3a931faed20b2314c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6540caa7beb945f0321bf38942587d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-32a4845ff65651415af840aed5ad1767&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-caa60f44fc47125398c7ec53a5186865&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2af3da83b586005637f4530b60892346&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17ee3298badd5c634297742f3bfdd8e4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd08cbda0f2618e783e7d18b1e718420&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b832bffca6f5b953e97047ac37cd38ec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dbdb6e100fb2bdb409feb08c479fa265</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168888</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Iron-Deficiency Anaemia">
      <data key="d0">Iron-Deficiency Anaemia</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Iron-deficiency anaemia is a blood disorder characterized by insufficient iron levels in the body, resulting in reduced red blood cell production and hemoglobin levels. This condition has been identified and confirmed through laboratory analysis of the patient's blood work and results.

The diagnosis of iron-deficiency anaemia in this patient is based on objective laboratory findings that demonstrate both the depleted iron stores and the consequent impact on red blood cell and hemoglobin production. The condition affects the overall blood composition and oxygen-carrying capacity of the circulatory system.

In this particular case, iron-deficiency anaemia has been revealed as a consequence of prolonged rectal bleeding, which represents an identifiable underlying cause for the patient's iron depletion and subsequent anaemic state. The laboratory confirmation of this condition provides clinical evidence of the pathological process occurring within the patient's hematologic system.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ed0783f447cb66336d0ee665a9a9ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17baf644d96495d064f9649f631230b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-299e0d28d253c37f9dddf4aef8eb2c94&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93f288f93598c3b3a931faed20b2314c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6540caa7beb945f0321bf38942587d0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d7dfbf9ae7bdd2da18160509a98a29b9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aea77867f87b397c2569ebf2e109e550&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-17ee3298badd5c634297742f3bfdd8e4</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168480</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Barrett's Oesophagus">
      <data key="d0">Barrett's Oesophagus</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Barrett's oesophagus is a premalignant, precancerous condition of the lower esophagus that is identified during endoscopic examination. The condition is characterized by metaplastic changes in the esophageal lining, where the normal squamous epithelium is replaced by columnar epithelium with intestinal-type mucosa. A key diagnostic feature of Barrett's oesophagus is the presence of high-grade dysplasia, which is observed and confirmed through endoscopy.

Barrett's oesophagus represents a significant clinical concern due to its potential for malignant transformation. The condition carries an increased risk of progression to esophageal adenocarcinoma, making accurate identification and monitoring through endoscopic evaluation essential for patient management. The presence of high-grade dysplasia within the metaplastic tissue further elevates the risk of cancer development and necessitates close clinical follow-up and appropriate therapeutic intervention.&lt;SEP&gt;A premalignant condition of the esophagus with high-grade dysplasia identified during endoscopy.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-ed0783f447cb66336d0ee665a9a9ae0c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-552541f5707dbc91dc2b39f24da42ff3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-359c4bdb901dcb37d2cf0fa307a2c571&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b0848622c01d4f566da1895987417746&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3d50fc57a8c14c7819b2950816abc682&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2af3da83b586005637f4530b60892346&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-12b0793fd5ff30936be7578fadb2f11c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-bd08cbda0f2618e783e7d18b1e718420&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-d99b348010e0859bf79ca469b926378b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168989</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Hepatic Metastases">
      <data key="d0">Hepatic Metastases</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Secondary liver tumors detected on CT abdomen imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Cancer spread to the liver identified through CT imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Cancer spread to the liver identified through CT imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Cancer spread to the liver identified on CT abdomen imaging.&lt;SEP&gt;Secondary tumors in the liver identified on CT abdomen imaging.</data>
