    <node id="Physical Examination">
      <data key="d0">Physical Examination</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Physical Examination is a clinical assessment method performed on a patient to identify and evaluate physical signs and symptoms through systematic observation and evaluation. This diagnostic procedure involves a comprehensive examination of the patient's body to detect any abnormal findings or clinical indicators.

During physical examinations, various cardiac and respiratory findings may be identified. Cardiac assessments can reveal irregular cardiac rhythm or irregular rhythm patterns, indicating potential arrhythmias or other cardiac abnormalities. Additionally, an S3 gallop—an abnormal heart sound—may be detected during auscultation. Respiratory examinations may reveal bilateral basal crepitations, which are abnormal crackling or rattling sounds heard in the lower lung fields bilaterally, often associated with fluid accumulation or other pulmonary pathology.

Physical examination serves as a fundamental clinical tool in patient assessment, enabling healthcare providers to detect physical signs that may indicate underlying medical conditions and inform subsequent diagnostic and therapeutic decisions.&lt;SEP&gt;Clinical assessment performed on the patient that revealed S3 gallop.&lt;SEP&gt;A clinical assessment performed on the patient that revealed bilateral basal crepitations and other physical findings.&lt;SEP&gt;Clinical assessment that revealed irregular heart rhythm in the patient.&lt;SEP&gt;Clinical assessment performed on the patient that revealed an S3 gallop.</data>
