    <node id="Dual Antiplatelet Therapy">
      <data key="d0">Dual Antiplatelet Therapy</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Dual Antiplatelet Therapy is a therapeutic intervention involving the concurrent administration of two antiplatelet medications to a patient. This treatment approach is initiated following clinical diagnosis, particularly in cases of acute non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI), to address and manage cardiac conditions effectively.

The primary clinical purpose of Dual Antiplatelet Therapy is to prevent blood clotting and reduce the risk of thrombotic events. By utilizing two antiplatelet agents simultaneously, this treatment regimen works to inhibit platelet aggregation and clot formation, thereby reducing the likelihood of serious cardiovascular complications. The therapy is administered as part of comprehensive cardiac care management to improve patient outcomes and prevent potentially life-threatening thromboembolic events.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-8a6870a0ae60e5e97ee38192a8c7cb33&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-13a80dbd998d7aced4f85f4e332b3980&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c23e378760ce2cf115e65e9075717448&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-24b0722d4e6a03efb1f886b8c96c34fd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-432f575b36f0861b9c262c0f7ea4613e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-51b315cb721376514a08823422d5c30f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a1f1f43b5a8581949513cce1ff0ab8de&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fa5295eee150f6d2e5bed021b15fafd0</data>
