    <node id="Decompensated Cirrhosis">
      <data key="d0">Decompensated Cirrhosis</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Decompensated cirrhosis is an advanced stage of liver disease characterized by significant loss of hepatic function and the failure of the liver's synthetic capabilities. This condition represents the final diagnosis for affected patients and constitutes a state of advanced liver failure.

The condition is marked by multiple pathological features, including hepatic dysfunction and portal hypertension. Decompensated cirrhosis manifests with clinical signs of liver failure, indicating that the organ has progressively lost its ability to perform essential metabolic and synthetic functions. The presence of portal hypertension—elevated pressure within the portal venous system—reflects the structural damage to the liver and contributes to the development of serious complications.

As a final diagnosis, decompensated cirrhosis signifies the terminal phase of chronic liver disease, in which compensatory mechanisms can no longer maintain adequate hepatic function. This stage typically follows a period of compensated cirrhosis, during which the liver, despite structural damage, had retained sufficient functional capacity. The transition to decompensation occurs when the liver can no longer sustain these compensatory processes, resulting in clinically evident liver failure and associated systemic complications.&lt;SEP&gt;The primary diagnosis indicating advanced liver disease with loss of hepatic synthetic function.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-17baf644d96495d064f9649f631230b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b0848622c01d4f566da1895987417746&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-299e0d28d253c37f9dddf4aef8eb2c94&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5efbbabff30dce7757a05e1d7b57eaa2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-93f288f93598c3b3a931faed20b2314c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4fb8802354fa5826fc6a61e1d4703650&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1693a9d96722a090fabd3e1bd2ba20a2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f78e14c615a6efcb86bacdcef718021&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-304f340ad4cf36f85eadeea2200b5890</data>
