    <node id="Bilateral Basal Crepitations">
      <data key="d0">Bilateral Basal Crepitations</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Bilateral Basal Crepitations

Bilateral basal crepitations refer to abnormal lung sounds detected during physical examination that are present on both sides at the base of the lungs. These findings are identified through auscultation and represent one of the key clinical indicators assessed during pulmonary examination.

The presence of bilateral basal crepitations is typically indicative of pulmonary pathology involving fluid accumulation within the lungs. These abnormal sounds suggest potential pulmonary congestion and are consistent with pulmonary edema, a condition characterized by excessive fluid in the lung tissue and alveoli. The bilateral nature of the finding—affecting both the lower lung bases symmetrically—indicates a systemic or widespread pulmonary process rather than a localized abnormality.

Clinically, bilateral basal crepitations serve as an important diagnostic indicator during physical examination that warrants further investigation to determine the underlying etiology of fluid accumulation in the lungs and to guide appropriate clinical management.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-64cd049e5c5b89e54dfbde1ab8bbcd95&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b0260e68b82e6826effdbcc686dec9cd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-51b315cb721376514a08823422d5c30f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8b9466306ab7d2011082fa69d4835ba8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-da9725a3a120031d9b91eb87eeb7ea97&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c2571e07f042a9f93f2e47306fa03981&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4004490c7f995b8c84484a113ba933ec&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e434022f7935c8daeaf7caba8c447e9f</data>
