    <node id="Foreign Body Aspiration">
      <data key="d0">Foreign Body Aspiration</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Foreign Body Aspiration is a medical condition characterized by the inhalation of a foreign object into the respiratory tract. This condition is typically suspected or diagnosed based on clinical presentation and physical examination findings.

The clinical presentation of Foreign Body Aspiration includes characteristic respiratory symptoms such as stridor and reduced breath sounds. Physical examination findings commonly associated with this condition include unilateral reduced breath sounds and wheeze, which serve as important diagnostic indicators. These clinical manifestations prompt healthcare providers to suspect Foreign Body Aspiration as the underlying diagnosis.

The diagnosis of Foreign Body Aspiration is established through a combination of clinical findings, physical examination results, and diagnostic imaging studies. The suspected diagnosis is based on the correlation between the patient's reported symptoms, observed physical examination findings, and imaging evidence that confirms the presence of an inhaled foreign object within the respiratory tract. The presence of unilateral rather than bilateral symptoms often suggests localization of the aspirated object to one side of the respiratory system, which aids in clinical assessment and management planning.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-6d5bcc445de13e0cbc298cdc386c5d44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-633b98afe9675d274497d13c770dc7a8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d8c12fa6d02482beb80341b410dc4fc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fe603f70880276dc53d591b2c6fc6ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c464148080eca020535a45a857530061&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ea49e51c9a44c10ef5253c942a3bd509&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-125eccf021b8ac36d38facc6f2707698&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e5211c9d4452573a55519727c0ef76b1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775169126</data>
