    <node id="Room Air">
      <data key="d0">Room Air</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Room air refers to the ambient air environment in which a patient's oxygen saturation is measured without the administration of supplemental oxygen. It serves as the baseline condition for assessing a patient's oxygenation status and respiratory function.

Room air represents the natural oxygen environment that the patient breathes under standard conditions. As a baseline measurement parameter, room air oxygen saturation readings provide essential clinical reference points for evaluating a patient's respiratory performance and determining whether supplemental oxygen therapy or other interventions may be necessary. The specific oxygen saturation values recorded under room air conditions vary depending on individual patient physiology and clinical status, with documented measurements ranging from 91% to 96% in different clinical contexts.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-6d5bcc445de13e0cbc298cdc386c5d44&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-633b98afe9675d274497d13c770dc7a8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fe603f70880276dc53d591b2c6fc6ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd85436604dc21edf42918a59c026df6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8eff0da2c4db4508c02bd09795c327d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e94bd709d2e35b86324f9ebf8cb380f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-125eccf021b8ac36d38facc6f2707698&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb2cd72190b2ba60ab4d0ac08898df5c</data>
