    <node id="Oxygen Saturation">
      <data key="d0">Oxygen Saturation</data>
      <data key="d1">data</data>
      <data key="d2">Oxygen Saturation

Oxygen saturation refers to the measured vital sign indicating the percentage of hemoglobin in the blood that is saturated with oxygen. The descriptions provided reflect multiple clinical measurements of this parameter across different patient presentations.

The most frequently documented oxygen saturation reading in the provided descriptions is 91% on room air, which appears across multiple clinical encounters. This level of oxygen saturation is consistently characterized as indicating mild hypoxemia, representing a mildly reduced blood oxygen level in the patient. Another commonly recorded measurement is 94% on room air, which is also noted as indicating mild hypoxemia. In contrast, one measurement documented 96% on room air, which is interpreted as indicating adequate oxygenation and represents a more favorable clinical status. Additionally, one description notes a critically low oxygen saturation measurement of 88% upon patient presentation, representing a more severe degree of hypoxemia than the mild cases.

These varying measurements suggest oxygen saturation assessments across different clinical timepoints or patient encounters, with most readings falling within the range that suggests at least mild oxygen insufficiency. The consistent measurement on room air—without supplemental oxygen—provides important context for interpreting the clinical significance of each reading. The range of documented values from 88% to 96% reflects the spectrum from critical hypoxemia to adequate oxygenation, indicating variability in the patient's oxygenation status either across time or among different clinical presentations.&lt;SEP&gt;The patient's oxygen saturation was measured at 88%, indicating significant hypoxemia requiring supplemental oxygen.&lt;SEP&gt;The patient's blood oxygen level measured at 94% on room air.&lt;SEP&gt;The patient's oxygen saturation measured at 96% on room air.&lt;SEP&gt;The patient's oxygen saturation measured at 94% on room air, indicating mild hypoxemia.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-633b98afe9675d274497d13c770dc7a8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-664a546642468c69e4060dadf0cf6259&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fe603f70880276dc53d591b2c6fc6ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-edefebc0c0ccf297dd9120097036b554&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cd85436604dc21edf42918a59c026df6&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c464148080eca020535a45a857530061&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8eff0da2c4db4508c02bd09795c327d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e94bd709d2e35b86324f9ebf8cb380f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ea49e51c9a44c10ef5253c942a3bd509&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-125eccf021b8ac36d38facc6f2707698&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb2cd72190b2ba60ab4d0ac08898df5c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e5211c9d4452573a55519727c0ef76b1</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775169127</data>
