    <node id="Chest Auscultation">
      <data key="d0">Chest Auscultation</data>
      <data key="d1">method</data>
      <data key="d2">Chest auscultation is a physical examination and diagnostic technique used to listen to and assess breath sounds within the patient's chest and lungs. This clinical method involves auscultating the chest to identify abnormalities and detect abnormal breathing patterns that may indicate underlying pulmonary conditions.

Chest auscultation can reveal various abnormal findings depending on the patient's condition. In some cases, it has revealed expiratory wheeze bilaterally, indicating abnormal sounds present in both lungs during the expiratory phase of breathing. In other instances, chest auscultation has demonstrated unilateral reduced breath sounds accompanied by wheeze, suggesting diminished air movement in one lung combined with wheezing sounds. Additionally, the technique has been used to identify tubular breathing patterns at the right base of the lungs, which represents another form of abnormal respiratory sound.

As a fundamental component of clinical examination, chest auscultation serves as an important diagnostic tool for detecting and characterizing respiratory abnormalities, enabling clinicians to assess pulmonary function and inform further diagnostic and therapeutic decisions.&lt;SEP&gt;Clinical examination technique used to listen to lung sounds and detect expiratory wheeze in the patient.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-664a546642468c69e4060dadf0cf6259&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9d8c12fa6d02482beb80341b410dc4fc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2fe603f70880276dc53d591b2c6fc6ca&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-edefebc0c0ccf297dd9120097036b554&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8eff0da2c4db4508c02bd09795c327d2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e94bd709d2e35b86324f9ebf8cb380f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ea49e51c9a44c10ef5253c942a3bd509&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-125eccf021b8ac36d38facc6f2707698&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cb2cd72190b2ba60ab4d0ac08898df5c</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1775168948</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
