    <edge source="MRI" target="Bone Marrow Oedema">
      <data key="d7">8.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The relation between Bone Marrow Oedema and MRI refers to the detection and visualization of bone marrow oedema through magnetic resonance imaging. MRI imaging has demonstrated the presence of bone marrow oedema in multiple anatomical locations, including affected joints, the knee, and the shoulder. This imaging modality serves as a diagnostic tool for identifying and characterizing bone marrow oedema, which represents fluid accumulation or swelling within the bone marrow space. The consistent findings across multiple MRI studies indicate that bone marrow oedema can be reliably detected in various joint regions, making MRI a valuable imaging technique for assessing this pathological condition. The relation encompasses the practical application of MRI technology in clinical diagnosis and monitoring of bone marrow oedema across different skeletal sites.</data>
