    <edge source="Endoscopy" target="Ulcerating Mass">
      <data key="d7">9.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The relation between Endoscopy and Ulcerating Mass describes a clinical finding identified during an endoscopic procedure. Endoscopy is a diagnostic technique that involves the visual inspection of internal body structures using an endoscope, a flexible tube equipped with a camera and light source. In this context, endoscopy was performed to visualize and document the presence of an ulcerating mass.

The ulcerating mass represents a pathological lesion characterized by tissue breakdown and ulceration. The endoscopic examination revealed the presence of this ulcerating mass, which was located at the gastro-oesophageal junction—the anatomical boundary between the stomach and the oesophagus (also known as the gastroesophageal junction or GE junction). This location is clinically significant as it is a common site for various pathological conditions, including malignancies and benign lesions.

The endoscopic findings documented the visualization and confirmation of the ulcerating mass at this specific anatomical site. This relation represents a crucial diagnostic correlation wherein the endoscopic procedure served as the investigative tool that enabled the identification and localization of the ulcerating mass, facilitating further clinical assessment, tissue sampling if indicated, and subsequent clinical management and treatment planning. The documentation of this finding is essential for establishing the diagnosis, determining the extent of the lesion, and guiding appropriate therapeutic interventions.&lt;SEP&gt;Endoscopy demonstrated the presence of the ulcerating mass at the gastro-oesophageal junction.</data>
      <data key="d9">abnormal identification,clinical finding,diagnostic discovery,diagnostic finding,diagnostic procedure,finding,imaging finding,imaging result,lesion identification,procedural finding,procedure finding,visualization</data>
