    <edge source="CT Thorax" target="Mediastinal Lymphadenopathy">
      <data key="d7">8.0</data>
      <data key="d8">CT Thorax, Mediastinal Lymphadenopathy is a radiological finding identified through computed tomography imaging of the thorax. This relation describes the detection of enlarged lymph nodes within the mediastinum, the central compartment of the thoracic cavity situated between the lungs.

The relation represents a significant imaging abnormality observed on CT thorax examinations. Mediastinal lymphadenopathy, as demonstrated through this imaging modality, indicates pathological enlargement of lymph nodes in the mediastinal region. This finding is clinically important as it can indicate various underlying conditions, including infection, malignancy, inflammatory diseases, or other systemic processes affecting the thoracic lymph nodes.

The presence of mediastinal lymphadenopathy on CT thorax represents a notable radiological observation that typically warrants further clinical correlation and investigation to determine the underlying etiology and appropriate management strategy.</data>
      <data key="d9">diagnostic finding,diagnostic result,imaging finding,imaging result,radiological evidence</data>
