    <edge source="Bronchoscopy" target="Endobronchial Tumour">
      <data key="d7">8.0</data>
      <data key="d8">The relation between Bronchoscopy and Endobronchial Tumour describes a clinical diagnostic finding in which a bronchoscopy procedure identifies the presence of an endobronchial tumour within a patient's airways. Bronchoscopy, an endoscopic examination technique that allows direct visualization of the tracheobronchial tree, serves as a key diagnostic tool for detecting endobronchial tumours—abnormal growths located within the bronchial passages.

During bronchoscopic examination, the procedure reveals an endobronchial tumour as a significant diagnostic finding. The tumour is identified and visualized within the patient's airways through direct airway visualization, enabling clinicians to assess the location, extent, and characteristics of the lesion. This relation is fundamental in respiratory medicine, as endobronchial tumours detected via bronchoscopy represent an important clinical discovery that guides subsequent management decisions, including staging, treatment planning, and prognostic assessment. The identification of such tumours during bronchoscopy constitutes a critical diagnostic outcome that directly impacts patient care and clinical decision-making.</data>
      <data key="d9">clinical detection,diagnostic finding,diagnostic method,diagnostic result,endoscopic finding,endoscopic procedure,procedural discovery,procedural finding,procedural result,procedure finding,tumor detection</data>
